REQUIREMENTS

1) GNU Scientific Library (http://www.gnu.org/software/gsl) development packages
   for your system (typically "gsl" and "gsl-devel").

2) You may also need some packages required by HOpenGL or by other Haskell libraries
   (e.g., gxorg-x11-devel freeglut-devel, etc.)

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
INSTALLATION 

$ runhaskell Setup.hs configure -p --prefix=$HOME
$ runhaskell Setup.hs build
$ runhaskell Setup.hs install --user

(You should also repeat these steps after a darcs pull.)

Alternatively, these commands and a few tests are automatically invoked by the script:

$ chmod u+x setup
$ ./setup

NOTE: The library must be used from another directory. For instance:

$ cd examples

Interactive:

examples$ ghci
Prelude> :m + GSL
Prelude GSL> realVector [1,0.5,3] <> complexVector [5,-i,3+i]
(loading packages...)
14.0 :+ 2.5
Prelude GSL> integrateQNG 1E-10 (^2) 0 1
(0.3333333333333333,3.700743415417188e-15)
Prelude GSL> :q
Leaving GHCi.

examples$ ghci demo.hs
*Main> main

Compiled:

examples$ ghc --make demo.hs
examples$ ./demo

Script:

examples$ runhaskell demo.hs

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
USING ATLAS OPTIMIZED LIBRARIES

The performance of some linear algebra computations with big matrices can
be significantly improved using ATLAS (http://math-atlas.sourceforge.net/).

They can be installed as a standalone package or as part of other systems.
For instance, GNU-Octave includes useful packages like atlas, fftw, gnuplot, etc.

To use the optimized libraries you only need a symbolic link to the
appropriate atlas blas available in your distribution. For instance,
in my ubuntu distribution I have added:

~/lib/GSL-0.5/ghc-6.5.20061004/libgslcblas.so -> /usr/lib/atlas/libblas.so.3.0

